---
import DocsLayout from '../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Architecture">
  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h1 class="section-title">System Architecture</h1>
      <p class="text-muted">Deep dive into the three-layer design and memory model</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Core Principle</h3>
        <p>
          A lock-free, thread-safe DOM using Arc-backed persistent data structures.
          Every mutation produces a new tree version that shares most of its nodes with the old version.
          Multiple threads read different versions simultaneously, no synchronization required.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Three-Layer Design</h2>

      <div class="card card-pad-xl architecture-diagram-container">
        <img src="/architecture-diagram.svg" alt="Three-layer architecture diagram" />
      </div>

      <div class="card architecture-card">
        <h3>Layer 1: Node Structure</h3>
        <p>
          Immutable <code>Node</code> with <code>Arc</code> wrapping and persistent containers.
          Children are <code>ImVector</code>, attributes are <code>ImHashMap</code>.
          This structure is the foundation, everything else is functions on Node.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card architecture-card">
        <h3>Layer 2: Mutation API</h3>
        <p>
          The <code>mutate()</code> function recursively clones only the nodes on the path.
          All other nodes remain shared via their <code>Arc</code> pointers. This is structural sharing in action.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card architecture-card">
        <h3>Layer 3: Concurrent Reader</h3>
        <p>
          Renderers (layout, paint) take a snapshot, an <code>Arc</code>, and traverse it without locks.
          Because the tree is immutable, concurrent reads are inherently thread-safe.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
<section>
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Memory Model</h2>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Before and After Mutation</h3>
        <div class="mutation-viz">
          <div class="viz-column">
            <div class="tree-box original">
              <code class="label">root</code>
              <div class="tree-list">
                <div>child 0 - Arc A</div>
                <div>child 1 - Arc B</div>
                <div>child 2 - Arc C</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="viz-caption">Original tree</p>
          </div>

          <div class="viz-arrow">to</div>

          <div class="viz-column">
            <div class="tree-box mutated">
              <code class="label">root</code>
              <div class="tree-list">
                <div>child 0 - Arc A</div>
                <div>child 1 - Arc D (new)</div>
                <div>child 2 - Arc C</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="viz-caption">New tree - siblings shared</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="card architecture-highlight">
          <h4>Result</h4>
          <p>
            For a 10,000-node tree mutating one leaf: 30 nodes copied, 9,970 shared (99.7% sharing).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Node Structure Deep Dive</h2>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Key Types</h3>
        <p>The core types use Arc for thread-safe sharing and ImVector for persistent children.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="grid-3">
        <div class="card">
          <h4>Why ImVector?</h4>
          <p>
            Persistent data structure shares most of its internal storage between versions.
            When you update one index, the new vector only allocates the path to that index.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4>Why Arc?</h4>
          <p>
            Atomic reference counting enables thread-safe sharing.
            Multiple owners can hold the same Node. When last Arc drops, memory frees.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h4>Why Generic Content?</h4>
          <p>
            Flexibility to store any content type (String, numbers, custom structs).
            The concrete type fixes content to String for DOM use.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Thread Safety Guarantees</h2>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Why No Locks?</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><code>Arc</code> is Sync + Send because Node is immutable after creation.</li>
          <li>Multiple threads can hold Arc to different versions of the tree simultaneously.</li>
          <li>The publish step is a single atomic pointer swap.</li>
          <li>Old readers continue on their snapshot; new readers see the new root. No blocking.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Invariants Table</h3>
        <table class="pointer-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Thread</th>
              <th>Holds</th>
              <th>Can Do</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>JS (writer)</td>
              <td><code>Arc</code> (mutable)</td>
              <td>mutate + swap root</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Layout</td>
              <td><code>Arc</code> (snapshot)</td>
              <td>Traverse safely</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Paint</td>
              <td><code>Arc</code> (snapshot)</td>
              <td>Traverse safely</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container text-center mb-xl">
    <a href="/walkthrough/node-structure" class="hero-cta">Continue to Phase 1 Walkthrough</a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>